            "content": "# Etymology Notes\n\n- **serendipity**: Coined by Horace Walpole in a 1754 letter, derived from \"The Three Princes of Serendip,\" a Persian fairy tale referring to Serendip (an old name for Ceylon, modern Sri Lanka), ultimately tracing back to Sanskrit *Simhaladvipa*.\n\n- **defenestration**: First recorded in 1620 from Latin *fenestra* (\"window\"), coined in reference to the Defenestration of Prague on May 23, 1618, when Protestant radicals threw Catholic deputies from a castle window — sparking the Thirty Years' War.\n\n- **sonder**: A modern neologism coined by John Koenig in 2012 for *The Dictionary of Obscure Sorrows*, defined as the realization that each random passerby is living a life as vivid and complex as one's own (no etymonline entry exists for this word).\n"
          },
